value.value: Serving or tending to restore health; a remedy.

An autoantibody against a red blood cell surface antigen that causes the cells to clump when the blood is cooled below the normal body temperature (the clumping is most pronounced at temperatures below 78 degrees). Presence of cold agglutinins may be indicative of mycoplasmal pneumonia, mononucleosis, mumps, measles, scarlet fever, some parasitic infections, cirrhosis of the liver, and some types of hemolytic anemia.
Unable to be evaluated.
Having strength, power, or intensity greater than average or expected.
Having strength, power, or intensity less than average or expected.
The area of the chest beneath the areola of the nipple.
A benign or malignant lesion typically arising in the period between infancy and adulthood.

label.value: Spaces Lined by One to Three Layers of Monotonous Atypical Cells Present

value.value: A saturated solution of formaldehyde, water, and typically another agent, most commonly methanol. In its typical form, formalin is 37% formaldehyde by weight (40% by volume), 6-13% methanol, and the rest water.
The likelihood or possibility that a specific state or condition will exist or that an action will occur.
A person who retrieves and summarizes information.

label.value: Dilated Terminal Duct Lobular Units Present

value.value: A morphologic finding indicating the presence of dilated terminal duct lobular units in a breast tissue sample.

label.value: Dilated Terminal Duct Lobular Units with Acini Lined by One or Two Layers of Columnar Epithelial Cells Present
Monomorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachycardia in which the QRS complexes have a uniform morphology. (CDISC)

label.value: Dilated Terminal Duct Lobular Units with Acini Lined by More than Two Layers of Columnar Epithelial Cells Present
Polymorphic Ventricular Tachycardia by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of a ventricular tachycardia in which the QRS complexes have a variable morphology and often rate. (CDISC)
An electrocardiographic finding in which the sinus rate fluctuates with the respiratory cycle. (CDISC)
A papilloma that arises from the conjunctival squamous epithelium. It is associated with human papillomavirus infection.

label.value: Wandering Atrial Pacemaker by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of a supraventricular arrhythmia characterized by 3 or more distinct P wave morphologies with an isoelectric baseline, variable PR intervals and no predominant atrial rhythm. The ventricular rate is typically below 100 beats per minute. (CDISC)

An electrocardiographic finding in which a failure of impulse formation or conduction in the sinus node produces prolongation of the P-P interval or dropped P waves. The threshold for the prolongation of the P-P interval is not well defined. (CDISC)

A derangement in the normal functioning of the sinoatrial node. Typically, SA node dysfunction is manifest as sinoatrial exit block or sinus arrest, but may present as an absolute or relative bradycardia in the presence of a stressor. It may be associated with bradycardia-tachycardia syndrome
A constellation of signs and symptoms which may include syncope, fatigue, dizziness, and alternating periods of bradycardia and atrial tachycardia, which is caused by sinoatrial node dysfunction.

label.value: Ectopic Atrial Rhythm by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of a regular atrial rhythm with atrial rate of less than 101 beats per minute which does not originate in the sinus node, and which is characterized by P waves whose morphology differs from the P wave morphology during sinus rhythm. (CDISC)

label.value: Short PR Interval by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of an abnormally short PR interval. Thresholds for different age, gender, and patient populations exist. (CDISC)

label.value: Prolonged PR Interval by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of a PR interval of more than 0.20 seconds in adults.

An electrocardiographic finding of a type of atrioventricular dissociation characterized by the atria (P waves) and ventricles (QRS complexes) beating at similar rates, although independently. (CDISC)

label.value: Paroxysmal Atrioventricular Block by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of the sudden onset of transient AV block, which is often associated with preexisting conduction disorders. (CDISC)
A form of representation in which distinct objects (or digits) are used to express or represent something in the real world.

label.value: Inappropriate Sinus Tachycardia by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of supraventricular tachycardia involving the sinus node in which a patient has an atypically high heart rate which cannot be explained by factors such as fever, exercise, hypovolemia, etc.
As an immediate result; having nothing intervening; without deviation or interruption.
Not as a direct effect or consequence; having intervening factors or persons or influences.

label.value: Ventricular Premature Complex by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the ventricles. The QRS morphology of these complexes is different from those of supraventricular origin. The QRS duration is often longer and the RR interval preceding the complexes is usually shorter than that of supraventricular beats. (CDISC)

label.value: Atrial Premature Complex by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of an ectopic impulse originating in the atria and not specifically in the sinus node. The P wave morphology of these complexes is often different from a sinus P wave and the RR intervals preceding these complexes is also shorter than those of the regular beats. (CDISC)

An electrocardiographic finding of initial slurring (delta wave) of the QRS complex due to the presence of an accessory pathway. This characteristic ECG pattern is typically seen in Wolff-Parkinson-White syndrome. (CDISC)
An electrocardiographic finding in which two premature ventricular complexes occur sequentially. (CDISC)
Any body structure resembling a flat circular plate.

label.value: Atrioventricular Reentrant Tachycardia by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of a regular supraventricular tachycardia which utilizes an atrioventricular bypass tract as its retrograde limb (orthodromic tachycardia) or as its antegrade limb (antidromic tachycardia). QRS complexes during sinus rhythm may show preexcitation. During orthodromic tachycardia the preexcitation is not present and a retrograde P wave may appear after the QRS complex. During antidromic tachycardia the QRS complex is preexcited. (CDISC)
See for the first time; identify.
Variety; quality, state, fact, or instance of being different.
Of, involving, or concerning a specific, local region such as a home or country.
Consisting of or involving two parts or components, often in pairs.

label.value: Accelerated Idioventricular Rhythm by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of idioventricular rhythm with a rate greater than 50 beats per minute. (CDISC)

label.value: Left Anterior Fascicular Block by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of a slightly widened QRS duration (typically less than 120 ms) with leftward frontal plane QRS axis and typically small Q waves in leads I and aVL. (CDISC)

label.value: Left Posterior Fascicular Block by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of an S1Q3 pattern and QRS axis greater than or equal to 120 degrees. It is usually seen in association with other abnormalities (e.g. RBBB or RVH). (CDISC)

label.value: Left Bundle Branch Block by ECG Finding

value.value: An electrocardiographic finding of a wide QRS complex with evidence of delayed conduction to the left ventricle, manifested as a widened initial portion of the QRS complex in leads V5, V6, I and aVL and with QRS duration greater than or equal to 120 ms. (CDISC)
